<div id="review_4392587315" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4392587315" />
    <a title="Rebecca Maye Holiday" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/133056070-rebecca-maye-holiday"><img alt="Rebecca Maye Holiday" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1638771856p2/133056070.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4392587315?book_show_action=true">Dec 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rebecca Maye Holiday" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rebecca Maye Holiday" href="/user/show/133056070-rebecca-maye-holiday">Rebecca Maye Holiday</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780312925888" href="/book/show/353024.Not_Without_My_Daughter">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/133056070-rebecca-maye-holiday?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/133056070-rebecca-maye-holiday?shelf=memoir">memoir</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/133056070-rebecca-maye-holiday?shelf=true-crime">true-crime</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/133056070-rebecca-maye-holiday?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4392587315" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2600912413908088142">There&apos;s been much debate over <i>Not Without My Daughter</i>&apos;s accuracy, both the book and its 1991 movie adaptation starring Sally Field. I&apos;ve heard many opinions on it. Some say it&apos;s a cathartic, chilling and inspirational tale about overcoming entrapment in a backwards religion. Others argue that the book is shamelessly racist and Islamophobic. I&apos;m not going to comment on the politics going on in this book, except to say that the people in Iran are like people anywhere else. You can get lovely, cari</span>
  <span id="freeText2600912413908088142" style="display:none">There's been much debate over <i>Not Without My Daughter</i>'s accuracy, both the book and its 1991 movie adaptation starring Sally Field. I've heard many opinions on it. Some say it's a cathartic, chilling and inspirational tale about overcoming entrapment in a backwards religion. Others argue that the book is shamelessly racist and Islamophobic. I'm not going to comment on the politics going on in this book, except to say that the people in Iran are like people anywhere else. You can get lovely, caring people... and you can get callous, vicious people. Religious extremism can be a catalyst for bad people to reign and do terrible things that they might otherwise not consider at all. Setting aside that <i>Not Without My Daughter</i> takes place in a revolutionized Iran, this book is, when you drill it down, a story of a battered woman trying to protect her child from an abusive husband.<br /><br />Betty Mahmoody lives as a housewife and mother in Michigan, the United States, with her Iranian-American husband (whom she affectionately calls "Moody"). Moody is a kind and generous husband, often giving Betty gifts, and he adores his daughter, Mahtob. Moody faces prejudice in the medical profession, and coupled with pressure from his family in Iran, he's frustrated about his place in life. Reluctantly, Betty agrees to take Mahtob to Iran with Moody to visit Moody's extended family. Even Moody himself is stunned by just how much his homeland has changed in the years since he's been gone, and his family reacts strangely to Betty's more liberal ways of attire and speaking. What begins as a two-week vacation becomes a real-life horror when Moody reveals that they're going to stay in Iran forever. Betty could simply divorce him and leave... but without Mahtob, as under Sharia law, Moody would automatically get custody.<br /><br />Surely one of the best parts of <i>Not Without My Daughter</i> is the variety of people in Iran who Betty meets. What's often pigeonholed as a primitive desert culture is shown to be a flowering world of wonderful people living in the shadows, kind and devoted people who reach out to help Betty. Most are native to Iran, but they understand Betty's plight, and as Muslims, they believe that the way Moody is treating her is wrong. Betty does raise some very good points. She notes that Moody swore on the Koran that she and Mahtob would return home safely in two days, which turns out to be a lie. This brings Moody's true devotion to Islam into question, as he bends it to his will to justify trapping Betty and Mahtob with him. He becomes more violent and ruthless, while Betty finds small fragments of solace in the few times she's permitted to go outdoors. Is <i>Not Without My Daughter</i> an unfair criticism of Islamic culture, or is it simply an evaluation of an abusive hypocrite who uses his religion as a tool of evil? After all, Betty points out the beautiful in Iran as much as the ugly, and Moody's peculiar ambivalence suggests a conflicted, broken person, Islamic influence or otherwise.<br /><br />Nobody who wasn't there with Betty in that home in Iran has any place judging the validity of her story, although by today's standards, she does include some dated stereotypes. This isn't an anti-Muslim book, but rather a book about a domestic abuser who happens to be in a position of foreign power over his wife. Similar things happen in China, in Russia, all over the world. The shackles of child custody can be strong enough to tie a spouse to their abusive partner forever, but Betty broke those shackles to save Mahtob, with the help of an underground moderate Muslim community, and smugglers in the mountains. The human capacity for empathy is stronger than any religious, political or racial divisions. Betty finds kindred spirits in people from a culture radically different from her own, and in doing so, she finds a new lease on life, as well.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2600912413908088142" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

